ething which is normally beyond his reach. He mixes this thing with his normal experiences and out of the mixture he makes a work of art.', 102, 0), (399438, 'I do not seek. I find.', 981, 0), (399439, 'The creation of a thousand forests is in one acorn.', 760, 0), (399440, 'The life of the creative man is led  directed and controlled by boredom. Avoiding boredom is one of our most important purposes.', 30031, 0), (399441, 'An artist is a creature driven by demons. He doesn''t know why they choose him and he''s usually too busy to wonder why.', 344, 0), (399442, 'No artist is ahead of his time. He is his time. It is just that others are behind the time.', 1209, 0), (399443, 'Doodling is the brooding of the hand.', 30031, 0), (399444, 'I am a choreographer. A choreographer is a poet. I do not create. God creates. I assemble  and I will steal from everywhere to do it.', 56813, 0), (399445, 'Workaholics are energized rather than enervated by their work - their energy paradoxically expands as it is expended.', 63163, 0), (399446, 'You lose it if you talk about it.', 110, 0), (399447, 'In creating  the only hard thing''s to begin  A grass-blade''s no easier to make than an oak.', 1247, 0), (399448, 'I can always be distracted by love  but eventually I get horny for my creativity.', 993, 0), (399449, 'The End of every maker is himself.', 63164, 0), (399450, 'Now I really make the little idea from clay  and I hold it in my hand. I can turn it  look at it from underneath  see it from one view  hold it against the sky  imagine it any size I like  and really be in control  almost like God creating something.', 19834, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (399451, 'No matter how old you get  if you can keep the desire to be creative  you''re keeping the man-child alive.', 21170, 0), (399452, 'What is originality? Undetected plagiarism.', 62527, 0), (399453, 'Originality is nothing but judicious imitation.', 808, 0), (399454, 'A hunch is creativity trying to tell you something.', 55471, 0), (399455, 'Style is a simple way of saying complicated things.', 2343, 0), (399456, 'What another would have done as well as you  do not do it. What another would have said as well as you  do not say it. What another would have written as well  do not write it. Be faithful to that which exists nowhere but in yourself- and thus make yourself indispensable.', 8, 0), (399457, 'It seems that the creative faculty and the critical faculty cannot exist together in their highest perfection.', 13860, 0), (399458, 'I must create a system or be enslaved by another man''s. I will not reason and compare  My business is to create.', 221, 0), (399459, 'In the beginning God created the Heaven and the earth. And the earth was without form  and void  and darkness was upon the face of the deep. And the Spirit of God moved upon the face of the waters. And God said  Let there be light  and there was light.', 5587, 0), (399460, 'Nature they say  doth dote  And cannot make a man Save on some worn-out plan  Repeating us by rote.', 1247, 0), (399461, 'All are but parts of one stupendous whole  Whose body Nature is  and God the soul.', 3348, 0), (399462, 'It is easier to suppose that the universe has existed from all eternity than to conceive a Being beyond its limits capable of creating it.', 165, 0), (399463, 'The world embarrasses me  and I cannot dream That this watch exists and has no watchmaker.', 808, 0), (399464, 'God is in the world  or nowhere  creating continually in us and around us. Insofar as man partakes of this creative process does he partake of the divine  of God  and that participation is his immortality ....', 2606, 0), (399465, 'You were placed on this earth to create  not to compete.', 5857, 0), (399466, 'Every moment of your life is infinitely creative and the universe is endlessly bountiful. )ust put forth a clear enough request  and everything your heart truly desires must come to you.', 39554, 0), (399467, 'There is no greater joy than that of feeling oneself a creator. The triumph of life is expressed by creation.', 1769, 0), (399468, 'Creativity is a central source of meaning in our lives . . . most of the things that are interesting  important  and human are the results of creativity . . . when we are involved in it  we feel that we are living more fully than during the rest of life.', 2151, 0), (399469, 'Creativeness often consists of merely turning up what is already there.', 63165, 0), (399470, 'A hunch is creativity trying to tell you something.', 55471, 0), (399471, 'I saw an angel in the block of marble and I just chiseled ''til I set him free.', 12364, 0), (399472, 'In creating  the only hard thing''s to begin  A grass-blade''s no easier to make than an oak.', 1247, 0), (399473, 'No matter how old you get  if you can keep the desire to be creative  you''re keeping the man-child alive.', 21170, 0), (399474, 'It is the child in man that is the source of his uniqueness and creativeness  and the playground is the optimal milieu for the unfolding of his capacities.', 2567, 0), (399475, 'Many times we will get more ideas and better ideas in two hours of creative loafing than in eight hours at a desk.', 11362, 0), (399476, 'If you are seeking creative ideas  go out walking. Angels whisper to a man when he goes for a walk.', 63166, 0), (399477, 'In God we trust  all others must pay cash.', 63167, 0), (399478, 'He that hath lost his credit is dead to the world.', 62334, 0), (399479, 'No man''s credit is as good as his money.', 13154, 0), (399480, 'Ah  take the cash  and let the credit go.', 1367, 0), (399481, 'Better be too credulous than too skeptical', 7652, 0), (399482, 'Let us believe neither half of the good people tell us of ourselves  nor half the evil they say of others.', 63168, 0), (399483, 'I wish I was as sure of anything as Macaulay is of everything.', 63169, 0), (399484, 'A small demerit extinguishes a long service.', 1348, 0), (399485, 'And the thing has been said and said well  have no scruple. Take it and copy it.', 348, 0), (399486, 'Jupiter is slow looking into his notebook  but he always looks.', 63170, 0), (399487, 'The number of malefactors authorizes not the crime.', 1348, 0), (399488, 'No one is entirely useless. Even the worst of us can serve as horrible examples.', 63171, 0), (399489, 'The faults of the burglar are the qualities of the financier.', 266, 0), (399490, 'He who excuses himself accuses himself. (Qui s''excuse  s''accuse.)', 33, 0), (399491, 'The study of crime begins with the knowledge of oneself.', 497, 0), (399492, 'Fear succeeds crime - it is its punishment.', 808, 0), (399493, 'All punishment is mischief. All punishment in itself is evil.', 2513, 0), (399494, 'Speaking generally  punishment hardens and numbs  it produces concentration  it sharpens the consciousness of alienation  it strengthens the power of resistance.', 11, 0), (399495, 'He only may chastise who loves.', 430, 0), (399496, 'If England treats her criminals the way she has treated me  she doesn''t deserve to have any.', 40, 0), (399497, 'It is fairly obvious that those who are in favour of the death penalty have more affinity with assassins than those who are not.', 3392, 0), (399498, 'Prisons don''t rehabilitate  they don''t punish  they don''t protect  so what the hell do they do?', 63172, 0), (399499, 'Capital punishment is as fundamentally wrong as a cure for crime as charity is wrong as a cure for poverty.', 1796, 0), (399500, 'The reformative effect of punishment is a belief that dies hard  chiefly  I think  because it is so satisfying to our sadistic impulses.', 95, 0);
