e returns to tell us of the road Which to discover we must travel too.', 1367, 0), (399787, 'I am dying  Egypt  dying.', 13, 0), (399788, 'Yet a little sleep  a little slumber  a little folding of the hands to sleep.', 33, 0), (399789, 'I have a rendezvous with Death At some disputed barricade.', 63212, 0), (399790, 'Till tired  he sleeps  and life''s poor play is o''er.', 3348, 0), (399791, 'To die: - to sleep: No more  and  by a sleep to say we end The heart-ache and the thousand natural shocks That flesh is heir to  ''tis a consummation Devoutly to be wished.', 13, 0), (399792, 'Nothing in his life Became him like the leaving it.', 13, 0), (399793, 'Death lies on her  like an untimely frost Upon the sweetest flower of all the field.', 13, 0), (399794, 'First our pleasures die - and then Our hopes  and then our fears - and when These are dead  the debt is due  Dust claims dust - and we die too.', 165, 0), (399795, 'God''s finger touched him  and he slept.', 62337, 0), (399796, 'Sunset and evening star  And one clear call for me! And may there be no moaning of the bar When I put out to sea.', 62337, 0), (399797, 'Nothing can happen more beautiful than death.', 1127, 0), (399798, 'For he who lives more lives than one More deaths than one must die.', 40, 0), (399799, 'A church debt is the devil''s salary.', 2175, 0), (399800, 'Wilt thou seal up the avenues of ill? Pay every debt as if God wrote the bill!', 760, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (399801, 'If you want the time to pass quickly  just give your note for 90 days.', 63213, 0), (399802, 'Owe no man anything.', 63214, 0), (399803, 'He that dies pays all debts.', 13, 0), (399804, 'A national debt  if it is not excessive  will be to us a national blessing.', 16733, 0), (399805, 'Debt is the worst poverty.', 63215, 0), (399806, 'Hood an ass with reverend purple. So you can hide his two ambitious ears  and he shall pass for a cathedral doctor.', 29394, 0), (399807, 'Proportion is almost impossible to human beings. There is no one who does not exaggerate.', 760, 0), (399808, 'Everything that deceives may be said to enchant.', 51, 0), (399809, 'We are never deceived  we deceive ourselves.', 62192, 0), (399810, 'All charming people have something to conceal  usually their total dependence on the appreciation of others.', 9518, 0), (399811, 'You k''n hide de fier  but what you guine do wid de smoke?', 29450, 0), (399812, 'Deep versed in books and shallow in himself.', 465, 0), (399813, 'Half the work that is done in the world is to make things appear what they are not.', 63216, 0), (399814, 'What we need is a rebirth of satire  of dissent  of irreverence  of an uncompromising insistence that phoniness is phony and platitudes are platitudinous.', 63217, 0), (399815, 'If the world will be gulled  let it be gulled.', 6261, 0), (399816, 'I give you bitter pills in sugar coating. The pills are harmless: the poison is in the sugar.', 63218, 0), (399817, 'I have known a vast quantity of nonsense talked about bad men not looking you in the face. Don''t trust that conventional idea. Dishonesty will stare honesty out of countenance  any day in the week  if there is anything to be got by it.', 96, 0), (399818, 'One should seek for the salutary in the unpleasant: if it is there  it is after all nectar. One should seek for the deceitful in the pleasant: if it is there it is after all poison.', 62341, 0), (399819, 'Deceive not thy physician  confessor  nor lawyer.', 3428, 0), (399820, 'Frank and explicit - this is the right line to take when you wish to conceal your own mind and to confuse the mind of others.', 1827, 0), (399821, 'A delusion  a mockery  and a snare.', 63219, 0), (399822, 'We are never deceived  we deceive ourselves.', 62192, 0), (399823, 'Which I wish to remark  -  And my language is plain  -  That for ways that are dark And for tricks that are vain  The heathen Chinese is peculiar.', 10748, 0), (399824, 'Hateful to me as are the gates of hell  Is he who  hiding one thing in his heart  Utters another.', 395, 0), (399825, 'You can fool some of the people all of the time  and all of the people some of the time  but you cannot fool all of the people all the time.', 1012, 0), (399826, 'It is double pleasure to deceive the deceiver.', 2843, 0), (399827, '"Will you walk into my parlour?" Said the spider to a fly: ''"Tis the prettiest little parlour That ever you did spy."', 8720, 0), (399828, 'One is easily fooled by that which one loves.', 1695, 0), (399829, 'Men and women everywhere must exercise deliberate selection to live wisely.', 63220, 0), (399830, 'Decision and determination are the engineer and fireman of our train to opportunity and success.', 63221, 0), (399831, 'The last of the human freedoms: to choose one''s attitude in any given set of circumstances  to choose one''s own way.', 63222, 0), (399832, 'Choice of attention ... is to the inner life what choice of action is to the outer. In both cases  a man is responsible for his choice and must accept the consequences  whatever they may be.', 219, 0), (399833, 'You are the one who must choose your place.', 14092, 0), (399834, 'Man does not simply exist  but always decides what his existence will be  what he will become in the next moment.', 63222, 0), (399835, 'Full maturity ... is achieved by realizing that you have choices to make.', 63223, 0), (399836, 'Wherever you see a successful business  someone once made a courageous decision.', 37852, 0), (399837, 'Life is just a series of trying to make up your mind.', 63224, 0), (399838, 'Life is just an endless chain of judgements. . . . The more imperfect our judgement  the less perfect our success.', 14130, 0), (399839, 'To know just what has do be done  then to do it  comprises the whole philosophy of practical life.', 63225, 0), (399840, 'Life is like a game of cards. The hand that is dealt you represents determinism  the way you play it is free will.', 8325, 0), (399841, 'Somehow we learn who we really are and then live with that decision.', 141, 0), (399842, 'Living is a constant process of deciding what we are going to do.', 63226, 0), (399843, 'Life is the sum of all your choices.', 532, 0), (399844, 'Life is the art of drawing sufficient conclusions from insufficient premises.', 4111, 0), (399845, 'The difficulty of life is in the choice.', 1282, 0), (399846, 'The strongest principle of growth lies in human choice.', 215, 0), (399847, 'As a man thinketh  so is he  and as a man chooseth  so is he.', 760, 0), (399848, 'Decisions determine destiny.', 63227, 0), (399849, 'Choices are the hinges of destiny.', 545, 0), (399850, 'Many of life''s circumstances are created by three basic choices: the disciplines you choose to keep  the people you chose to be with  and the laws you choose to obey.', 63228, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (399851, 'You don''t get to choose how you''re going to die. Or when. You can only decide how you''re going to live. Now.', 7820, 0), (399852, 'Look for your choices  pick the best one  then go with it.', 44727, 0), (399853, 'Rules of society are nothing  one''s conscience is the umpire.', 63229, 0), (399854, 'No matter how lovesick a woman is  she shouldn''t take the first pill that comes along.', 62254, 0), (399855, 'Form the habit of making decisions when your spirit is fresh ... to let dark moods lead is like choosing cowards to command armies.', 37070, 0), (399856, 'One must either accept some theory or else believe one''s own instinct or follow the world''s opinion.', 1267, 0), (399857, 'Decide which is the line of conduct that presents the fewest drawbacks and then follow it out as being the best one  because one never finds anything perfectly pure and unmixed  or exempt from danger.', 947, 0), (399858, 'A problem clearly stated is a problem half solved.', 40351, 0), (399859, 'We must make the choices that enable us to fulfill the deepest capacities of our real selves.', 123, 0), (399860, 'Choose always the way that seems the best  however rough it may be  custom will soon render it easy and agreeable.', 464, 0), (399861, 'Where an opinion is general  it is usually correct.', 24, 0), (399862, 'In forty hours I shall be in battle  with little information  and on the spur of the moment will have to make the most momentous decisions. But I believe that one''s spirit enlarges with responsibility and that  with God''s help  I shall make them  and make them right.', 62937, 0), (399863, 'Once the "what" is decided  the "how" always follows. We must not make the "how" an excuse for not facing and accepting the "what."', 442, 0), (399864, 'In each action we must look beyond the action at our past  present and future state  and at others whom it affects  and see the relation of all those things. And then we shall be very cautious.', 144, 0), (399865, 'One''s mind has a way of making itself up in the background  and it suddenly becomes clear what one means to do.', 62857, 0), (399866, 'Not all of your decisions will be correct. None of us is perfect. But if you get into the habit of making decisions  experience will develop your judgment to a point where more and more of your decisions will be right. After all  it is better to be right 51 percent of the time and get something done  than it is to get nothing done because you fear to reach a decision.', 63230, 0), (399867, 'Decide on what you think is right  and stick to it.', 215, 0), (399868, 'Continually one faces the horrible matter of making decisions. The solution ... is  as far as possible  to avoid conscious rational decisions and choices  simply to do what you find yourself doing  to float in the great current of life with as little friction as possible  to allow things to settle themselves  as indeed they do with the most infallible certainty.', 8661, 0), (399869, 'When making a decision of minor importance  I have always found it advantageous to consider all the pros and cons. In vital matters  however  such as the choice of a mate or a profession  the decision should come from the unconscious  from somewhere within ourselves. In the important decisions of personal life  we should be governed  I think  by the deep inner needs of our nature.', 555, 0), (399870, 'Pick battles big enough to matter  small enough to win.', 63231, 0), (399871, 'Wisdom consists in being able to distinguish among dangers and make a choice of the least harmful.', 947, 0), (399872, 'I think we should follow a simple rule: if we can take the worst  take the risk.', 62254, 0), (399873, 'Human foresight often leaves its proudest possessor only a choice of evils.', 432, 0), (399874, 'When one bases his life on principle  99 percent of his decisions are already made.', 33, 0), (399875, 'The best we can do is size up the chances  calculate the risks involved  estimate our ability to deal with them  and then make our plans with confidence.', 1796, 0), (399876, 'In case of doubt  decide in favor of what is correct.', 15784, 0), (399877, 'Each man must for himself alone decide what is right and what is wrong  which course is patriotic and which isn''t. You cannot shirk this and be a man. To decide against your conviction is to be an unqualified and inexcusable traitor  both to yourself and to your country  let men label you as they may.', 286, 0), (399878, 'People "died" all the time. ... Parts of them died when they made the wrong kinds of decisions-decisions against life. Sometimes they died bit by bit until finally they were just living corpses walking around. If you were perceptive you could see it in their eyes  the fire had gone out ... you always knew when you made a decision against life. ... The door clicked and you were safe inside- safe and dead.', 1407, 0), (399879, 'What I emphasize is for people to make choices based not on fear  but on what really gives them a sense of fulfillment.', 63232, 0), (399880, 'We lose the fear of making decisions  great and small  as we realize that should our choice prove wrong we can  if we will  learn from the experience.', 4747, 0), (399881, 'History is a stern judge.', 63233, 0), (399882, 'I get a little angry about this highhanded scrapping of the look of things. What else have we to go by? How else can the average person form an opinion of a girl''s sense of values or even of her chastity except by the looks of her conduct?', 63234, 0), (399883, 'You wouldn''t want to be caught wearing cheap perfume  would you? Then why do you want to wear cheap perfume on your conduct?', 63234, 0), (399884, 'The difference between weakness and wickedness is much less than people suppose  and the consequences are nearly always the same.', 63235, 0), (399885, 'Authority without wisdom is like a heavy axe without an edge  fitter to bruise than to polish.', 1211, 0), (399886, 'One faces the future with one''s past.', 442, 0), (399887, 'Our deeds still travel with us from afar  and what we have been makes us what we are.', 215, 0), (399888, 'You must not change one thing  one pebble  one grain of sand  until you know what good and evil will follow on that act.', 62247, 0), (399889, 'The beginning of compunction is the beginning of a new life.', 215, 0), (399890, 'The Pilgrims didn''t have any experience when they landed here. Hell  if experience was that important  we''d never have anybody walking on the moon.', 63236, 0), (399891, 'Each person has a literature inside them. But when people lose language  when they have to experiment with putting their thoughts together on the spot-that''s what I love most. That''s where character lives.', 21122, 0), (399892, 'There is no data on the future.', 63237, 0), (399893, 'The most important fact about Spaceship Earth: an instruction book didn''t come with it.', 11496, 0), (399894, 'Life is the only art that we are required to practice without preparation  and without being allowed the preliminary trials  the failures and botches  that are essential for the training of a mere beginner.', 13474, 0), (399895, 'Time has told me less than I need to know.', 63238, 0), (399896, 'I learn by going where I have to go.', 1085, 0), (399897, 'Life is like playing a violin in public and learning the instrument as one goes on.', 4111, 0), (399898, 'We don''t have enough time to premeditate all our actions.', 62195, 0), (399899, 'Every year  if not every day  we have to wager our salvation upon some prophecy based upon imperfect knowledge.', 24754, 0), (399900, 'Faith ... acts promptly and boldly on the occasion  on slender evidence.', 62299, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (399901, 'A decision is an action you must take when you have information so incomplete that the answer does not suggest itself.', 63239, 0), (399902, 'She knew in her heart that to be without optimism  that core of reasonless hope in the spirit  rather than the brain  was a fatal flaw  the seed of death.', 14652, 0), (399903, 'When faith is supported by facts or by logic it ceases to be faith.', 749, 0), (399904, 'How far would Moses have gone if he had taken a poll in Egypt?', 16121, 0), (399905, 'Better to be without logic than without feeling.', 42, 0), (399906, 'The will to be totally rational is the will to be made out of glass and steel: and to use others as if they were glass and steel.', 8930, 0), (399907, 'In the three years I played ball  we won six  lost seventeen and tied two. Some statistician ... calculated that we won 75 percent of the games we didn''t lose.', 63240, 0), (399908, 'Imagination took the reins  and Reason  slow-paced  though surefooted  was unequal to a race with so eccentric and flighty a companion.', 18866, 0), (399909, 'Many persons of high intelligence have notoriously poor judgement.', 4317, 0), (399910, 'How dangerous can false reasoning prove!', 139, 0), (399911, 'The tendency of modern science is to reduce proof to absurdity by continually reducing absurdity to proof.', 4111, 0), (399912, 'Say you were standing with one foot in the oven and one foot in an ice bucket. According to the percentage people  you would be perfectly comfortable.', 63241, 0), (399913, 'Logic is the art of going wrong with confidence.', 38001, 0), (399914, 'Reason  with most people  means their own opinions.', 8948, 0), (399915, 'Logic pervades the world  the limits of the world are also the limits of logic.', 1163, 0), (399916, 'Man is a reasoning  rather than a reasonable  animal.', 16733, 0), (399917, 'False conclusions which have been reasoned out are infinitely worse than blind impulse.', 2053, 0), (399918, 'If you do everything you should do  and do not do anything you should not do  you will  according to the best available statistics  live exactly eighteen hours longer than you would otherwise.', 63242, 0), (399919, 'Decisions  particularly important ones  have always made me sleepy  perhaps because I know that I will have to make them by instinct  and thinking things out is only what other people tell me I should do.', 1991, 0), (399920, 'Statistics are no substitute for judgement.', 46469, 0), (399921, 'It is the heart always that sees before the head can see.', 3061, 0), (399922, 'Facts are stubborn things  but statistics are more pliable.', 2120, 0), (399923, 'A true history of human events would show that a far larger proportion of our acts are the result of sudden impulse and accident than of that reason of which we so much boast.', 63243, 0), (399924, 'It is always thus  impaled by a state of mind which is destined not to last  that we make our irrevocable decisions.', 450, 0), (399925, 'A power greater than any human being helped make this decision.', 63244, 0), (399926, 'He who reflects too much will achieve little.', 62240, 0), (399927, 'The opportunity is often lost by deliberating.', 2904, 0), (399928, 'The percentage of mistakes in quick decisions is no greater than in long-drawn-out vacillations  and the effect of decisiveness itself "makes things go" and creates confidence.', 58349, 0), (399929, 'Deliberation often loses a good chance.', 62593, 0), (399930, 'The mania of thinking renders one unfit for every activity.', 348, 0), (399931, 'When possible make the decisions now  even if action is in the future. A revised decision usually is better than one reached at the last moment.', 63245, 0), (399932, 'We spend our days in deliberating  and we end them without coming to any resolve.', 63246, 0), (399933, 'If you think too long  you think wrong.', 63247, 0), (399934, 'You decide you''ll wait for your pitch. Then as the ball starts toward the plate  you think about your stance. And then you think about your swing. And then you realize that the ball that went past you for a strike was your pitch.', 63248, 0), (399935, 'The soul of dispatch is decision.', 8948, 0), (399936, 'The moment a question comes to your mind  see yourself mentally taking hold of it and disposing of it. In that moment... you learn to become the decider and not the vacillator. Thus you build character.', 63249, 0), (399937, 'So what do we do? Anything. Something. So long as we just don''t sit there. If we screw it up  start over. Try something else. If we wait until we''ve satisfied all the uncertainties  it may be too late.', 11247, 0), (399938, 'Often greater risk is involved in postponement than in making a wrong decision.', 63250, 0), (399939, 'Some persons are very decisive when it comes to avoiding decisions.', 37592, 0), (399940, 'Do not wait for ideal circumstances  nor the best opportunities  they will never come.', 62399, 0), (399941, 'There comes a time when you''ve got to say  "Let''s get off our asses and go ..." I have always found that if I move with 75 percent or more of the facts I usually never regret it. It''s the guys who wait to have everything perfect that drive you crazy.', 11247, 0), (399942, 'Conditions are never just right. People who delay action until all factors are favorable do nothing.', 5249, 0), (399943, 'Common sense does not ask an impossible chessboard  but takes the one before it and plays the game.', 24952, 0), (399944, 'He who postpones the hour of living is like the rustic who waits for the river to run out before he crosses.', 2542, 0), (399945, 'If you wait for inspiration you''ll be standing on the corner after the parade is a mile down the street.', 63251, 0), (399946, 'Nothing at all will be attempted if all possible objections must first be overcome.', 2087, 0), (399947, 'It is the characteristic excellence of the strong man that he can bring momentous issues to the fore and make a decision about them. The weak are always forced to decide between alternatives they have not chosen themselves.', 741, 0), (399948, 'Alternatives  and particularly desirable alternatives  grow only on imaginary trees.', 653, 0), (399949, 'The more one does and sees and feels  the more one is able to do  and the more genuine may be one''s own appreciation of fundamental things like home  and love  and understanding companionship.', 1646, 0), (399950, 'Our danger is not too few  but too many options ... to be puzzled by innumerable alternatives.', 63252, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (399951, 'The absence of alternatives clears the mind marvelously.', 2393, 0), (399952, 'I couldn''t claim that I have never felt the urge to explore evil  but when you descend into hell you have to be very careful.', 21453, 0), (399953, 'If decisions were a choice between alternatives  decisions would come easy. Decision is the selection and formulation of alternatives.', 63253, 0), (399954, 'You cannot have your cake and eat it.', 33, 0), (399955, 'It is better to arm and strengthen your hero  than to disarm and enfeeble your foe.', 3187, 0), (399956, 'You cannot sell the cow and sup the milk.', 33, 0), (399957, 'There is only one answer to destruc-tiveness and that is creativity.', 63254, 0), (399958, 'A door must either be shut or open.', 33, 0), (399959, 'Here''s a rule I recommend. Never practice two vices at once.', 755, 0), (399960, 'You cannot serve God and Mammon.', 5587, 0), (399961, 'Between two stools one sits on the ground.', 7630, 0), (399962, 'When you cannot make up your mind between two evenly balanced courses of action  choose the bolder.', 63255, 0), (399963, 'When confronted with two courses of action I jot down on a piece of paper all the arguments in favor of each one  then on the opposite side I write the arguments against each one. Then by weighing the arguments pro and con and cancelling them out  one against the other  I take the course indicated by what remains.', 1077, 0), (399964, 'There are two ways of spreading light: to be the candle or the mirror that reflects it.', 426, 0), (399965, 'You cannot have it both ways.', 33, 0), (399966, 'I would sort out all the arguments and see which belonged to fear and which to creativeness. Other things being equal  I would make the decision which had the larger number of creative reasons on its side.', 62244, 0), (399967, 'Of two evils  choose the less.', 33, 0), (399968, 'Of two evils  choose the prettier.', 34473, 0), (399969, 'Where bad''s the best  bad must be the choice.', 33, 0), (399970, 'Both choices are painful  but only one is therapeutic.', 63256, 0), (399971, 'God offers to every mind its choice between truth and repose. Take which you please-you can never have both.', 760, 0), (399972, 'Necessity relieves us from the embarrassment of choice.', 62195, 0), (399973, 'When you have to make a choice and don''t make it  that is in itself a choice.', 1782, 0), (399974, 'A man without decision can never be said to belong to himself  he is as a wave of the sea  or a feather in the air which every breeze blows about.', 63257, 0), (399975, 'Nothing is so exhausting as indecision  and nothing is so futile.', 95, 0), (399976, 'Not to decide is to decide.', 14381, 0), (399977, 'Decision is a sharp knife that cuts clean and straight  indecision  a dull one that hacks and tears and leaves ragged edges behind it.', 63258, 0), (399978, 'There is no more miserable human being than one in whom nothing is habitual but indecision.', 1782, 0), (399979, 'In not making the decision  you''ve made one. Not doing something is the same as doing it.', 63259, 0), (399980, 'There is a time when we must firmly choose the course we will follow  or the relentless drift of events will make the decision for us.', 63260, 0), (399981, 'You can only predict things after they''ve happened.', 2291, 0), (399982, 'It is the mark of a good action that it appears inevitable  in retrospect.', 449, 0), (399983, 'No one knows what he can to do until he tries.', 2904, 0), (399984, 'Of all paths a man could strike into  there is  at any given moment  a best path which  here and now  it were of all things wisest for him to do. To find this path  and walk in it  is the one thing needful for him.', 3061, 0), (399985, 'Decisions  particularly important ones  have always made me sleepy  perhaps because I know that I will have to make them by instinct  and thinking things out is only what other people tell me I should do.', 1991, 0), (399986, '